            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.XV.R1</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shew the faults of mothers, and their consequences</span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">This entry clearly relates to Dickens&rsquo;s illustration of Mrs. Markleham&rsquo;s carelessness, and its significance to the Strong subplot. Its phrasing, however, also gestures to the novel&rsquo;s broader interest in parental failure and the insufficiency of traditional family structures. With reference to this installment, the command to &ldquo;shew the faults of mothers&rdquo; can as easily be applied to Mrs. Steerforth, whose pride prevents her recognition of the gravity of her son&rsquo;s actions. It is worth remembering that, after Steerforth's death, Rosa lays the blame for his mistakes (and his fate) on his &ldquo;exacting, proud, punctilious, selfish&rdquo; mother: \"She has sown this. Let her moan for the harvest she reaps to-day!\" (DC 806-7).</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"
